result.execSummary:
The defendant Dominique Lavelle Williams was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Dominique Lavelle Williams is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Dominique Lavelle Williams was found guilty of Possess w/Intent-THC (<=200 grams) [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(h)1.
  • Dominique Lavelle Williams was found guilty of Maintain Drug Trafficking Place [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.42(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Dominique Lavelle Williams in court with Attorney Cole J White.  Defendant Dominique Lavelle Williams in custody.  Denis John Stingl appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Matter here for a plea hearing.  AS TO COUNTS #1, #2 AND #3: On State's motion, Court ordered COUNTS #1, #2 AND #3 DISMISSED.  

AS TO COUNTS #4 AND #5:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgment of conviction entered.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court advised defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  

Court ordered defendant REMANDED into the custody of the Milwaukee County Sheriff's Department.  Matter set for sentencing to May 3, 2016 at 1:30pm in Br. 30, Judge Conen's court.
